    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-12-14T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-12-14T12:00:00-05:00" n="881"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d881">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.1928/475: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Panama</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Flexer</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Panama</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-12-14T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 14, 1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 5:47 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>169. 1. Referring to Department’s telegram No. 65, October 25, noon. First
                    meeting scheduled December 16.</p>
                <p>With reference to paragraph 1–C of memorandum of points agreed upon by the
                    President of the United States and President Arias, transmitted by the
                    Department’s instruction No. 3, October 20, 1933,<note n="14" xml:id="d881fn14">
                        <ref target="frus1933v05#pg_865">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1933, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, p. 865</ref>.</note> confirmation is
                    requested of my view that the suggested surcharge would be based upon retail
                    commissary prices to employees, which are, I am informed, identical to prices of
                    quantity sales to ships. Canal Zone representatives have given reason for
                    anticipating contention that basis of surcharge is not established and might
                    equally refer to landed costs.</p>
                <p>“Other articles” to which surcharge might apply are construed to be embraced in
                    interpretation given in minutes of 14th meeting, paragraph 2. Referring first
                    paragraph Department’s telegram of December 9, 7 [<hi rend="italic">5</hi>]
                        p.m.<note n="15" xml:id="d881fn15">Not printed.</note> First meeting
                    scheduled December 17, representatives of Commanding General but not of governor
                    attending. Please refer to Legation’s despatch No. 51, April 25, 1935.<note
                        n="15" xml:id="d881fn1">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Flexer</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
